## 14. Explanations by Level

> [!NOTE]
> **Beginner:** We pasted a piece of code from TradingView onto our site. It creates a "mini browser window" (iframe) that shows their website inside ours. When you click it, it just takes you to their website. Our backend doesn't know anything about the prices.

> [!TIP]
> **Intermediate:** We are using TradingView's provided external Javascript widget. During the React component's `useEffect` lifecycle, we dynamically inject their script. This script fetches an iframe that maintains its own data connection to TradingView's servers. Because the iframe is cross-origin, clicks on the internal anchor tags redirect the parent window to TradingView.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Advanced Architecture:** The current implementation is a decoupled, client-side inclusion strategy utilizing third-party iframes. This offloads real-time data streaming (WebSocket/SSE) and charting canvas rendering entirely to the vendor. However, it violates domain encapsulation, resulting in session leakage (users leaving the platform) and vendor lock-in. 
> 
> **Enterprise-Grade Recommendation:** To maintain user retention, we must implement an API-driven architecture. The Node.js microservices layer should subscribe to a primary market data vendor via WebSockets, normalize the data payload, and push it to the React frontend via our own WebSocket Gateway. The frontend will consume this stream to hydrate open-source, unbranded canvas charting libraries (e.g., TV Lightweight Charts or Apache ECharts), ensuring complete control over the routing and user experience.
